##South Korea has seen a surge of 52 confirmed cases, with the worst-hit areas beginning to spread to military camps

The prime minister, Ding Shijun, said he would designate Daegu city and Qingdaojun of North Gyeongsang Province as special management areas for infectious diseases and resolutely take relevant measures to prevent and control the epidemic. Of the 14,660 people tested, 2,707 have yet to be tested.

On the morning of February 21, South Korea's central epidemic prevention department reported 52 new cases of newly diagnosed pneumonia, bringing the total number of confirmed cases in the country to 156. Meanwhile, the South Korean navy and air force have confirmed the infection in active duty servicemen. As an epidemic prevention policy, the Ministry of National Defense decided to restrict officers and soldiers from going out on the 22nd.

According to the source of the Interface News, there are currently three active duty soldiers in the Korean military confirmed to be diagnosed. They are a 22-year-old man from the Jeju Island Navy, a 31-year-old man from North Chungcheong Province and a 25-year-old man from South Chungcheong Province Air Force. The news has been confirmed in the Korean central daily.

According to Yonhap, the first confirmed case in the South Korean military was a marine serving in Jeju Island. He began his holiday in Taegu on February 13, returned to Jeju Volcanic Island and Lava Tubes by plane on the afternoon of February 18 and returned to his unit. He returned to the army on February 20 after receiving a viral test at a hospital screening clinic for cough and other symptoms.

A 31-year-old man serving in the North Chungcheong Province army is an active-duty officer (lieutenant) and his girlfriend is a member of the new World Taegu Church. The officer, who had fever and other symptoms, was transferred to the National Guard of the United States for treatment, South Korea's joongang Ilbo reported.

On the morning of the 21st, a 25-year-old Air Force lieutenant serving in South Chungcheong Province was also diagnosed and transferred to the National Armed Forces Hospital.

In South Korea, mass infections in Taegu and North Gyeongsang Province have become major outbreaks, with dozens of members of the new World Taegu Church confirmed. Of the 52 newly confirmed cases today, 41 occurred in the Taegu and North Gyeongsang Province regions, of which 39 were related to the new World Taegu Church. President Moon jae-in has ordered a thorough investigation of people who attended church services and funerals in Daegu Xintiandi.

In addition, five nurses in the Psychiatric Department of a hospital in Qingdao County, North Gyeongsang Province, were infected with new coronavirus pneumonia. The health department tested 600 patients and medical staff in the hospital for viral nucleic acid, and 16 of them were positive.

In order to prevent the spread of the epidemic, the Ministry of National Defense decided to restrict officers and soldiers from going out from the 22nd, with the exception of special cases such as pre-retirement leave and bereavement leave.

In addition, Republic of Korea Armed Forces is investigating the number of troops who went on leave in Taegu and North Gyeongsang Province earlier this month. According to military sources, in the first round of the investigation, more than 1,000 officers and soldiers from a certain unit visited the Taegu and Qingbei areas after the 10th of this month. The figure is expected to be higher after the results of the investigation conducted by the armed forces.

Yonhap said Republic of Korea Armed Forces currently has a number of large troops stationed in the Taegu and Gyeongbuk region, including the army's second combat command units, the Air Quartermaster Command and the 11th Combat Aviation Regiment.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
South Korean Prime Minister Chung Sye-kyun. Source: Yonhap

In view of the importance of the two regions to the South Korean military and national defense, State Premier Ding Sejun said on the morning of the 21st, when he chaired an expanded meeting of the Central Emergency Management Headquarters, daegu city, Qingshang North Road County will be designated as a special infectious disease management area, and decisively take relevant measures to prevent and control the epidemic.

Ding said the government would take special measures in the area to provide beds and human and material support. With the cumulative number of confirmed cases in the country exceeding 100 and community-acquired infections occurring in some areas, the government will take the situation in hand and respond with APLOMB. In the future, the focus of epidemic prevention will shift from preventing the virus from entering the country from abroad to preventing community-acquired infections in the country, to do everything in our power to overcome the epidemic.

As of 9:00 am on the 21st, 14,660 people had been tested for the new coronavirus in South Korea, of whom 11,953 were negative and 2,707 were pending results, according to the South Korean Central Epidemic Prevention Department.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Statistics of the Central Epidemic Prevention Headquarters.

In addition to the military's ban on travel as part of its epidemic prevention policy, South Korea's Ministry of Education has decided to conduct a nationwide survey of foreign elementary and middle school students, including both current students and the entire student body that submitted applications, on whether they had visited China recently. The survey included information on whether the foreign students had recently visited mainland China, Hong Kong and Macao, and when they would return from their stay abroad.

In addition, the Ministry of Education has recommended that schools ban students who have visited mainland China, Hong Kong and Macau in the past 14 days from attending classes. Schools are responsible for checking the health status of students twice a day. Schools with more than 30 per cent of the total number of students visiting China in the near future can postpone the start of classes after consultation with education and epidemic prevention authorities.
